+#: applications/config/option/PhabricatorSecurityConfigOptions.php:54
+#, php-format
+msgid ""
+"By default, Phabricator serves files from the same domain the application is served from. This is convenient, but presents a security risk.\n"
+"\n"
+"You should configure a CDN or alternate file domain to mitigate this risk. Configuring a CDN will also improve performance. See [[ %s | %s ]] for instructions."
+msgstr ""
+
+#: applications/config/option/PhabricatorSecurityConfigOptions.php:83
+#, php-format
+msgid ""
+"If the web server responds to both HTTP and HTTPS requests but you want users to connect with only HTTPS, you can set this to true to make Phabricator redirect HTTP requests to HTTPS.\n"
+"\n"
+"Normally, you should just configure your server not to accept HTTP traffic, but this setting may be useful if you originally used HTTP and have now switched to HTTPS but don't want to break old links, or if your webserver sits behind a load balancer which terminates HTTPS connections and you can not reasonably configure more granular behavior there.\n"
+"\n"
+"IMPORTANT: Phabricator determines if a request is HTTPS or not by examining the PHP `%s` variable. If you run Apache/mod_php this will probably be set correctly for you automatically, but if you run Phabricator as CGI/FCGI (e.g., through nginx or lighttpd), you need to configure your web server so that it passes the value correctly based on the connection type."
+msgstr ""
+
+#: applications/config/option/PhabricatorSecurityConfigOptions.php:164
+#, php-format
+msgid "When users write comments which have URIs, they'll be automatically linked if the protocol appears in this set. This whitelist is primarily to prevent security issues like %s URIs."
+msgstr ""
+
+#: applications/config/option/PhabricatorSecurityConfigOptions.php:231
+msgid "If you enable this, linked YouTube videos will be embedded inline. This has mild security implications (you'll leak referrers to YouTube) and is pretty silly (but sort of awesome)."
+msgstr ""
+
+#: applications/config/option/PhabricatorSecurityConfigOptions.php:242
+msgid "Blacklist subnets to prevent user-initiated outbound requests."
+msgstr ""
+
+#: applications/config/option/PhabricatorSecurityConfigOptions.php:246
+msgid ""
+"Phabricator users can make requests to other services from the Phabricator host in some circumstances (for example, by creating a repository with a remote URL or having Phabricator fetch an image from a remote server).\n"
+"\n"
+"This may represent a security vulnerability if services on the same subnet will accept commands or reveal private information over unauthenticated HTTP GET, based on the source IP address. In particular, all hosts in EC2 have access to such a service.\n"
+"\n"
+"This option defines a list of netblocks which Phabricator will decline to connect to. Generally, you should list all private IP space here."
+msgstr ""
+
+#: applications/config/option/PhabricatorSecurityConfigOptions.php:260
+msgid "No Outbound Requests"
+msgstr ""
+
+#: applications/config/option/PhabricatorSecurityConfigOptions.php:265
+msgid "Use HSTS"
+msgstr ""
+
+#: applications/config/option/PhabricatorSecurityConfigOptions.php:266
+msgid "Do Not Use HSTS"
+msgstr ""
+
+#: applications/config/option/PhabricatorSecurityConfigOptions.php:268
+msgid "Enable HTTP Strict Transport Security (HSTS)."
+msgstr ""
+
+#: applications/config/option/PhabricatorSecurityConfigOptions.php:271
+msgid ""
+"HTTP Strict Transport Security (HSTS) sends a header which instructs browsers that the site should only be accessed over HTTPS, never HTTP. This defuses an attack where an adversary gains access to your network, then proxies requests through an unsecured link.\n"
+"\n"
+"Do not enable this option if you serve (or plan to ever serve) unsecured content over plain HTTP. It is very difficult to undo this change once users' browsers have accepted the setting."
+msgstr ""
+
+#: applications/config/option/PhabricatorSecurityConfigOptions.php:296
+#, php-format
+msgid "Config option '%s' is invalid. The URI must start with '%s' or '%s'."
+msgstr ""
